which I wrote for people like

00:02:53.811 --> 00:02:54.440
you.
 

00:02:54.440 --> 00:02:56.788
Then you'll read Persian
Letters, not all of it.

00:02:56.788 --> 00:03:00.490
That would be a rather lengthy
day or so.

00:03:00.490 --> 00:03:02.370
You'll read excerpts in
Persian Letters,

00:03:02.370 --> 00:03:07.908
and Montesquieu talks about
relations between West and East,

00:03:07.908 --> 00:03:12.734
and it's a phenomenal moment in
the history of the

00:03:12.734 --> 00:03:14.310
Enlightenment.
 

00:03:14.310 --> 00:03:18.319
Then you have a pause where
you're basically just reading

00:03:18.319 --> 00:03:19.658
me,
for better or for worse,

00:03:19.658 --> 00:03:23.018
but I hope for better,
until you get to Ã‰mile

00:03:23.018 --> 00:03:26.479
Zola, his great novel,
Germinal,

00:03:26.479 --> 00:03:28.438
which is a classic.
 

00:03:28.438 --> 00:03:34.262
Zola was the first sort of
naturalist novelist,

00:03:34.262 --> 00:03:36.919
at least in France.
 

00:03:36.919 --> 00:03:39.843
When he wrote Germinal,
germinal means budding,

00:03:39.843 --> 00:03:41.389
like the budding of trees.
 

00:03:41.389 --> 00:03:45.110
But he means the budding of
people being aware of themselves

00:03:45.110 --> 00:03:45.930
as workers.
 

00:03:45.930 --> 00:03:49.569
He went down to the mines in
the north of France in the

00:03:49.569 --> 00:03:50.110
Anzin.
 

00:03:50.110 --> 00:03:53.586
One of the heroes of the book
is a woman called Catherine,

00:03:53.586 --> 00:03:56.942
who is fifteen years old,
but has seen a lot of life for

00:03:56.942 --> 00:03:58.650
being fifteen years old.
 

00:03:58.650 --> 00:04:02.758
When Zola wrote
Germinal,

00:04:02.758 --> 00:04:06.915
he went down into the mines to
look at fifteen-year-old young

00:04:06.915 --> 00:04:09.150
women,
barely older than girls,

00:04:09.150 --> 00:04:12.158
working in the mines twelve
hours a day.

00:04:12.158 --> 00:04:15.080
It's a book that resounds with
reality.

00:04:15.080 --> 00:04:19.432
It's really kind of an amazing
book, and I think you'll like

00:04:19.432 --> 00:04:19.949
that.
 

00:04:19.949 --> 00:04:21.269
I hope you will.
 

00:04:21.269 --> 00:04:25.110
Then Helmut Smith's The
Butcher's Tale is about

00:04:25.110 --> 00:04:28.589
accusations of ritual murder in
a German town.

00:04:28.589 --> 00:04:33.012
It's about the second German
Reich, and it's about

00:04:33.012 --> 00:04:38.250
anti-Semitism in a small place
with bigger consequences.

00:04:38.250 --> 00:04:43.675
George Orwell went off to fight
the good fight in Spain during

00:04:43.675 --> 00:04:48.129
the Spanish Civil War,
where it was sort of a dry run

00:04:48.129 --> 00:04:53.850
for an even more horrible war,
and even more horrible fascists.

00:04:53.850 --> 00:05:00.000
It's about his engagement and
disillusionment in the Spanish

00:05:00.000 --> 00:05:03.639
republican forces,
the loyalist forces,

00:05:03.639 --> 00:05:07.947
and about the tensions and the
duplicity of Stalin's folks

00:05:07.947 --> 00:05:12.709
undercutting the Trotskyites and
undercutting the anarchists.

00:05:12.709 --> 00:05:15.480
It's one of those classics
that's a classic for a very good

00:05:15.480 --> 00:05:15.910
reason.
 

00:05:15.910 --> 00:05:18.439
It's really a marvelous read.
 

00:05:18.439 --> 00:05:20.250
Finally, there's Ordinary
Men.

00:05:20.250 --> 00:05:22.350
I go to Poland a lot.
 

00:05:22.350 --> 00:05:25.384
In the last couple of years
I've been there four or five

00:05:25.384 --> 00:05:27.976
times for various reasons,
and I'd never been to

00:05:27.976 --> 00:05:28.750
Auschwitz.
 

00:05:28.750 --> 00:05:32.069
I went to Auschwitz a year ago.
 

00:05:32.069 --> 00:05:33.790
I don't know,
some of you have probably been

00:05:33.790 --> 00:05:34.110
there.
 

00:05:34.110 --> 00:05:37.550
As you're going through the
horror of it all,

00:05:37.550 --> 00:05:40.791
and as you're seeing empty
suitcases with people's names on

00:05:40.791 --> 00:05:43.250
them that the people don't exist
anymore,

00:05:43.250 --> 00:05:45.889
and you're seeing baby shoes
and things like that.

00:05:45.889 --> 00:05:47.990
You think, "Who could have
done this?

00:05:47.990 --> 00:05:52.702
Who could have gone out and
simply, in an assembly line way,

00:05:52.702 --> 00:05:54.459
killed people?"
 

00:05:54.459 --> 00:05:57.810
Or in fields around Lodz,
which was a large industrial

00:05:57.810 --> 00:06:00.983
town and still is in Poland,
simply gone out and blown the

00:06:00.983 --> 00:06:02.389
brains out of mothers,
babies,

00:06:02.389 --> 00:06:04.319
grandmothers,
and anybody they found.

00:06:04.319 --> 00:06:05.519
Who could have done it?
 

00:06:05.519 --> 00:06:09.509
Well, the answer that Chris
Browning has is ordinary men.

00:06:09.509 --> 00:06:14.726
And he had the quite brilliant
idea of looking at a German

00:06:14.726 --> 00:06:17.286
unit,
essentially policemen from

00:06:17.286 --> 00:06:19.774
Hamburg,
the port town of Hamburg,

00:06:19.774 --> 00:06:22.129
an old important Hanseatic
port.

00:06:22.129 --> 00:06:26.064
And he follows them from the
lives of very ordinary people

00:06:26.064 --> 00:06:29.793
into the killing fields,
it was nothing less than that,

00:06:29.793 --> 00:06:30.759
of Poland.
 

00:06:30.759 --> 00:06:32.120
It's also short.
 

00:06:32.120 --> 00:06:35.519
Germinal is long,
but these other ones are short.

00:06:35.519 --> 00:06:37.331
It's gripping.
 

00:06:37.331 --> 00:06:39.920
It's quite amazing.
 

00:06:39.920 --> 00:06:41.720
So, those are the books.
 

