00:12:53.836 --> 00:12:56.110
in Fontainebleau,
which is just southeast of

00:12:56.110 --> 00:12:56.639
Paris.
 

00:12:56.639 --> 00:12:59.379
He's a boy who hadn't been
there before.

00:12:59.379 --> 00:13:01.110
He's a Jewish boy.
 

00:13:01.110 --> 00:13:05.288
It's about his friendship with
this boy, and what happens.

00:13:05.288 --> 00:13:09.354
At the end, it's not a happy
film, but it's a great,

00:13:09.354 --> 00:13:10.389
great film.
 

00:13:10.389 --> 00:13:11.419
What else?
 

00:13:11.419 --> 00:13:11.629
What to say?
 

00:13:11.629 --> 00:13:12.639
There's a midterm.
 

00:13:12.639 --> 00:13:15.308
I don't like to waste a lecture
giving a midterm.

00:13:15.308 --> 00:13:19.741
I would rather give a lecture,
but we have to have something

00:13:19.741 --> 00:13:21.168
to report to you.
 

00:13:21.168 --> 00:13:24.047
If you tube it,
if you don't do very well at

00:13:24.047 --> 00:13:27.460
all, we don't count it as much
as if you do well.

00:13:27.460 --> 00:13:29.120
People ask these questions,
I know.

00:13:29.120 --> 00:13:30.509
How much is it worth?
 

00:13:30.509 --> 00:13:33.511
Geez, there's more to live than
grades, but it's something like

00:13:33.511 --> 00:13:36.370
twenty-five percent and the
paper is twenty-five percent.

00:13:36.370 --> 00:13:40.722
Section participation is ten
percent, whatever we work out,

00:13:40.722 --> 00:13:42.000
then the final.
 

00:13:42.000 --> 00:13:48.500
It's an exercise in seeing how
you're doing.

00:13:48.500 --> 00:13:53.686
It really is no big deal,
but it will help you pull the

00:13:53.686 --> 00:13:56.759
themes of the course together.
 

00:13:56.759 --> 00:13:58.840
It's no scary situation.
 

00:13:58.840 --> 00:14:03.418
We all live in this sort of A-,
B range.

00:14:03.418 --> 00:14:05.616
I'll tell you,
a couple of years ago I ran

00:14:05.616 --> 00:14:06.690
into this student.
 

00:14:06.690 --> 00:14:09.313
When I run into students,
I'm a friendly guy and I see

00:14:09.313 --> 00:14:11.740
people, and I say,
"Hi, how are you?"

00:14:11.740 --> 00:14:12.600
I ran into this one person.
 

00:14:12.600 --> 00:14:13.690
I said, "Hi,
how are you?"

00:14:13.690 --> 00:14:17.429
And she went,
"Oh, hello."

00:14:17.429 --> 00:14:18.408
Oh?
 

00:14:18.408 --> 00:14:20.615
I remembered her name and I
went and looked it up,

00:14:20.615 --> 00:14:21.649
and there was the B .
 

00:14:21.649 --> 00:14:24.019
It wasn't that,
"Hi, how are you?

00:14:24.019 --> 00:14:26.908
A- or A," but whatever.
 

00:14:26.908 --> 00:14:29.418
I'm sure she had all A's in the
other courses,

00:14:29.418 --> 00:14:32.761
and a B is not the end of the
world, and most people get A's,

00:14:32.761 --> 00:14:33.710
but whatever.
 

00:14:33.710 --> 00:14:34.610
You have to take the midterm.
 

00:14:34.610 --> 00:14:35.980
That's the way they run it here.
 

00:14:35.980 --> 00:14:38.822
That's not my idea,
so that's what we're going to

00:14:38.822 --> 00:14:39.120
do.
 

00:14:39.120 --> 00:14:42.808
Okay, now I'm going to talk
about some of the themes.

00:14:42.808 --> 00:14:45.759
At the end, I'm going to read
you a poem.

00:14:45.759 --> 00:14:50.830
I started history in a serious
way because I read this poem.

00:14:50.830 --> 00:14:53.740
So, I'll leave that until the
end of it.

00:14:53.740 --> 00:14:55.500
I didn't got to Yale.
 

00:14:55.500 --> 00:14:59.835
I went to the University of
Michigan, maize and blue

00:14:59.835 --> 00:15:03.149
forever, very sad since last
weekend.

00:15:03.149 --> 00:15:05.879
I came from Portland, Oregon.
 

00:15:05.879 --> 00:15:07.101
I don't know if any of you come
from Portland,

00:15:07.101 --> 00:15:08.080
Oregon, but that's where I'm
from.

00:15:08.080 --> 00:15:11.764
When I went off to Michigan,
I'd been at a Jesuit high

00:15:11.764 --> 00:15:12.389
school.
 

00:15:12.389 --> 00:15:15.073
Jesuit high school was a sports
factory, in part,

00:15:15.073 --> 00:15:18.428
but it was a very good school,
but it was very repressive.

00:15:18.428 --> 00:15:22.682
I went off to the University of
Michigan after having been in

00:15:22.682 --> 00:15:24.879
Jesuit school for four years.
 

00:15:24.879 --> 00:15:26.470
It was wine, women, and song.
 

00:15:26.470 --> 00:15:31.408
There weren't enough in the
middle and probably too much of

00:15:31.408 --> 00:15:32.428
the first.
 

00:15:32.428 --> 00:15:37.110
My first semester I got a 1.93
grade point average,

00:15:37.110 --> 00:15:42.539
and my mother asked me if that
was on a two-point scale.

00:15:42.539 --> 00:15:43.929
I'm serious.
 

00:15:43.929 --> 00:15:45.799
I had an F.
 

00:15:45.799 --> 00:15:47.408
I shouldn't laugh at myself.
 

00:15:47.408 --> 00:15:48.442
My kids say,
"Oh, my god,

00:15:48.442 --> 00:15:49.620
not the same story again."
 

00:15:49.620 --> 00:15:52.542
But I got an F,
and I got two C's,

00:15:52.542 --> 00:15:53.960
and I got a B.
 

00:15:53.960 --> 00:15:57.508
The people I hung around with
in Ann Arbor were so

00:15:57.508 --> 00:16:00.043
unaccomplished,
some of them anyway,

00:16:00.043 --> 00:16:03.808
that they thought I was smart
because I got a B.

00:16:03.808 --> 00:16:05.643
I'd go by in the dining room
and they'd say,

00:16:05.643 --> 00:16:06.710
"He got a B."
 

00:16:06.710 --> 00:16:08.559
They asked me to tutor them.
 

00:16:08.559 --> 00:16:10.028
Can you imagine that?
 

00:16:10.028 --> 00:16:12.168
Some of the people that I hung
around with were amazing.

00:16:12.168 --> 00:16:14.580
You may even know people like
that, but I don't think so.

00:16:14.580 --> 00:16:17.602
But one of the guys that I
knew, I've got to get back to

00:16:17.602 --> 00:16:20.296
the topic in a minute,
but I just thought of this,

00:16:20.296 --> 00:16:22.549
was sort of the king of
malapropisms.

00:16:22.549 --> 00:16:24.028
One day he was going on and on.
 

00:16:24.028 --> 00:16:25.330
These are the people I hung
around with.

00:16:25.330 --> 00:16:28.373
He was going on and on about
this good meal that he had of

00:16:28.373 --> 00:16:30.990
one course after another,
and it was fantastic.

00:16:30.990 --> 00:16:34.990
It was a really good
restaurant, and somebody snuck

00:16:34.990 --> 00:16:36.269
him some wine.
 

00:16:36.269 --> 00:16:38.504
Finally, I'm tired of the whole
thing and I said,

00:16:38.504 --> 00:16:39.808
"Was it gratis?"
 

00:16:39.808 --> 00:16:41.820
He said, "No,
it was chicken."

00:16:41.820 --> 00:16:43.985
Those are the people that I
hung around with at the

00:16:43.985 --> 00:16:45.070
University of Michigan.
 

00:16:45.070 --> 00:16:47.875
But I've taught here a long
time and I stand by maize and

00:16:47.875 --> 00:16:49.080
blue, but I love Yale.
 

00:16:49.080 --> 00:16:50.842
One of the things I love about
Yale is being able to teach

00:16:50.842 --> 00:16:51.399
people like you.
 

00:16:51.399 --> 00:16:53.759
And I mean it,
and I love this course,

00:16:53.759 --> 00:16:57.460
so I hope that you will enjoy
it, if indeed you take it.

00:16:57.460 --> 00:16:59.450
What about some of the themes?
 

00:16:59.450 --> 00:17:01.308
What kind of stuff are we going
to do?

00:17:01.308 --> 00:17:05.980
Could you get some syllabi for
some of those folks back there?

00:17:05.980 --> 00:17:08.279
They're up on the thing.
 

00:17:08.279 --> 00:17:09.619
Thanks a lot.
 

00:17:09.619 --> 00:17:11.490
A couple of themes.
 

00:17:11.490 --> 00:17:13.468
I don't believe,
and I've never believed,

00:17:13.468 --> 00:17:15.200
that history is a series of
bins.

00:17:15.200 --> 00:17:17.296
I guess I wrote that in the
book, but that you open up and

00:17:17.296 --> 00:17:19.210
you say, "Well,
there goes the Enlightenment.

00:17:19.210 --> 00:17:20.450
Shut that baby down."
 

00:17:20.450 --> 00:17:22.534
Then you open up the next one,
and here comes

00:17:22.534 --> 00:17:25.140
eighteenth-century rivalries,
and you shut that baby.

00:17:25.140 --> 00:17:28.131
Then the French Revolution,
"Oh, I know all about that

00:17:28.131 --> 00:17:28.750
now."
 

00:17:28.750 --> 00:17:31.457
Pretty soon you go on to
Russian Revolution eventually,

00:17:31.457 --> 00:17:32.210
and all that.
 

00:17:32.210 --> 00:17:35.615
To do a course like this where
you're going to learn much of

00:17:35.615 --> 00:17:38.848
what is important to know about
western civilization,

00:17:38.848 --> 00:17:40.976
I do believe,
if you do the reading and

00:17:40.976 --> 00:17:43.608
stuff,
and if you enjoy the lectures,

00:17:43.608 --> 00:17:47.536
there have to be some threads
that go all the way through that

00:17:47.536 --> 00:17:50.240
make it worth it so you learn
something.

00:17:50.240 --> 00:17:52.920
One is certainly state-making.
 

00:17:52.920 --> 00:17:54.798
Even if you take a sort of
federalized,

00:17:54.798 --> 00:17:58.556
decentralized state like with
this very bizarre electoral

00:17:58.556 --> 00:18:02.865
system like the United States,
that the growth of modern

00:18:02.865 --> 00:18:05.042
states,
it doesn't really just come in

00:18:05.042 --> 00:18:07.700
the twentieth century with the
welfare state beginning in

00:18:07.700 --> 00:18:09.526
England,
and even before that in some

00:18:09.526 --> 00:18:11.685
other places,
insurance programs and things

00:18:11.685 --> 00:18:12.250
like that.
 

00:18:12.250 --> 00:18:15.358
It begins with the
consolidation of state power in

00:18:15.358 --> 00:18:18.660
the late Middle Ages with
territorial monarchies,

00:18:18.660 --> 00:18:23.410
the Spanish, and the French,
and the English monarchies.

00:18:23.410 --> 00:18:26.269
It has a lot to do with the
growth of absolute rule.

00:18:26.269 --> 00:18:29.511
That's what I'm going to talk
about next time,

00:18:29.511 --> 00:18:31.528
absolute rule,
absolutism.

00:18:31.528 --> 00:18:35.589
The growth of standing armies,
huge standing armies,

00:18:35.589 --> 00:18:38.694
never seen before,
of big forts built on

00:18:38.694 --> 00:18:39.808
frontiers.
 

00:18:39.808 --> 00:18:43.118
It has a lot to do with
bureaucrats who could extract

00:18:43.118 --> 00:18:45.220
resources from ordinary people.
 

00:18:45.220 --> 00:18:48.237
A lot of the rich didn't pay
anything or hardly anything at

00:18:48.237 --> 00:18:48.548
all.
 

00:18:48.548 --> 00:18:51.055
It has to do with an
allegiance, a dynastic

00:18:51.055 --> 00:18:54.277
allegiance that could be
transferred later to a nation,

00:18:54.277 --> 00:18:55.650
the idea of nation.
 

00:18:55.650 --> 00:18:57.509
That starts in the eighteenth
century.

00:18:57.509 --> 00:18:59.130
It doesn't start in the
nineteenth century.

00:18:59.130 --> 00:19:03.038
It starts in the eighteenth
century, at least in Britain.

00:19:03.038 --> 00:19:06.960
That's an argument that we'll
make also.

00:19:06.960 --> 00:19:11.559
In 1500, which is kind of when
that book gets rolling--they

00:19:11.559 --> 00:19:16.000
only start in about 1648--there
were about 1500 different

00:19:16.000 --> 00:19:18.538
territorial units in Europe.
 

00:19:18.538 --> 00:19:22.368
Some were no bigger than
Archbishop's Garden in Germany,

00:19:22.368 --> 00:19:24.913
and some were larger
states--not yet what they are

00:19:24.913 --> 00:19:29.230
now in terms of size,
such as France,

00:19:29.230 --> 00:19:35.220
which expanded under Louis XIV
into Alsace and Lorraine,

00:19:35.220 --> 00:19:37.730
and various other places.
 

00:19:37.730 --> 00:19:40.670
But there's about 1500
territorial units.

00:19:40.670 --> 00:19:43.750
In 1890, there were thirty.
 

00:19:43.750 --> 00:19:46.390
So, the consolidation of state
power,

00:19:46.390 --> 00:19:49.220
which is looking at it from the
state out,

00:19:49.220 --> 00:19:54.761
or the emergence of an identity
where you see yourself as German

00:19:54.761 --> 00:19:59.884
as opposed to Bavarian,
French as opposed to Gascon or

00:19:59.884 --> 00:20:04.010
Provencal,
Spanish as opposed to Castilian

00:20:04.010 --> 00:20:06.519
or as opposed to Catalan.
 

00:20:06.519 --> 00:20:11.711
The Catalan language was
illegal until 1975,

00:20:11.711 --> 00:20:17.267
until Francisco Franco finally
croaked in 1975,

00:20:17.267 --> 00:20:19.200
in November.
 

00:20:19.200 --> 00:20:22.019
This is a great phrase;
I wish I'd said it originally.

00:20:22.019 --> 00:20:25.480
I don't know who said it,
but someone once said that a

00:20:25.480 --> 00:20:28.420
language is a dialect with a
powerful army.

00:20:28.420 --> 00:20:28.779
That's it.
 

00:20:28.779 --> 00:20:29.808
That's true.
 

00:20:29.808 --> 00:20:32.368
France at the time of the
French Revolution,

00:20:32.368 --> 00:20:34.750
half the people in France knew
French.

00:20:34.750 --> 00:20:35.859
There was bilingualism.
 

00:20:35.859 --> 00:20:37.150
You could know Catalan.
 

00:20:37.150 --> 00:20:39.670
You could know Auvergnat patois.
 

00:20:39.670 --> 00:20:43.240
We live in the south of France
where a lot of old people still

00:20:43.240 --> 00:20:46.108
speak a patois,
though that's mostly dying out.

00:20:46.108 --> 00:20:50.940
How does it come that identity,
a sense of allegiance to a

00:20:50.940 --> 00:20:52.720
state or a country?
 

00:20:52.720 --> 00:20:55.598
Not everybody,
but how does it come to 1914

00:20:55.598 --> 00:20:58.682
when people go marching off to
get killed singing the

00:20:58.682 --> 00:21:02.059
Marseillaise,
the French national anthem,

00:21:02.059 --> 00:21:03.650
in pretty good French?
 

00:21:03.650 --> 00:21:05.118
How does that happen?
 

00:21:05.118 --> 00:21:08.180
How does a state increase its
reach?

00:21:08.180 --> 00:21:10.818
How is the modern world created?
 

00:21:10.818 --> 00:21:13.748
We call this process,
it's a clumsy word,

00:21:13.748 --> 00:21:15.140
but state-making.
 

00:21:15.140 --> 00:21:16.170
How do states form?
 

00:21:16.170 --> 00:21:18.950
The other side of this is how
do identities change?

00:21:18.950 --> 00:21:20.737
In the sixteenth century,
seventeenth century,

00:21:20.737 --> 00:21:21.730
ask somebody they were.
 

00:21:21.730 --> 00:21:23.690
Say, "Who are you?"
 

00:21:23.690 --> 00:21:25.210
They'd say, "I'm so and so.
 

00:21:25.210 --> 00:21:26.390
I'm of this family."
 

00:21:26.390 --> 00:21:28.164
Or, "I am
Protestant,"

00:21:28.164 --> 00:21:31.660
if it was the sixteenth century
or late sixteenth century,

00:21:31.660 --> 00:21:34.829
any time after 1520s or 1530s
in parts of Germany.

00:21:34.829 --> 00:21:35.269
"I'm Protestant.
 

00:21:35.269 --> 00:21:37.788
I'm Jewish."
 

00:21:37.788 --> 00:21:40.970
In much of the Balkans,
"I am Muslim."

00:21:40.970 --> 00:21:43.858
In most of Europe,
"I am Catholic."

00:21:43.858 --> 00:21:46.558
In Eastern Europe,
"I am Russian Orthodox.

00:21:46.558 --> 00:21:50.710
I live in a mir (village) in
Russia."

00:21:50.710 --> 00:21:53.173
How does that happen by the end
of the nineteenth century that

00:21:53.173 --> 00:21:55.365
people have,
even Russia as they're starving

00:21:55.365 --> 00:21:57.731
to death,
starving in the famine that

00:21:57.731 --> 00:21:59.314
Tolstoy,
the great writer,

00:21:59.314 --> 00:22:01.088
called the world's attention
to.

00:22:01.088 --> 00:22:03.740
A lot of them died in fields
thinking,

00:22:03.740 --> 00:22:06.618
"only if the czar only
knew that we were starving,

00:22:06.618 --> 00:22:09.009
and that his ministers were
treating us bad,

00:22:09.009 --> 00:22:10.369
how angry he would be."
 

00:22:10.369 --> 00:22:11.210
Well, they didn't get it.
 

00:22:11.210 --> 00:22:14.108
They didn't know that the czar
could have given one damn.

00:22:14.108 --> 00:22:18.633
But the allegiance to the czar,
the sense of being Russian or

00:22:18.633 --> 00:22:23.156
being dominated by the Russian
czar, is something that had to

00:22:23.156 --> 00:22:24.588
be constructed.
 

00:22:24.588 --> 00:22:29.239
So, the state constructs its
ability to extract taxes,

00:22:29.239 --> 00:22:33.624
extract bodies for national
armies, also to provide

00:22:33.624 --> 00:22:37.660
resources, but identities are
transformed.

00:22:37.660 --> 00:22:42.096
So, I give this as an example,
because state-making is one of

00:22:42.096 --> 00:22:45.868
the themes that kind of ties
everything together.

00:22:45.868 --> 00:22:49.606
This course ends in 1945,
but look at the problems in the

00:22:49.606 --> 00:22:52.210
post-communist world of
state-making.

00:22:52.210 --> 00:22:55.505
Look what's going on in
Georgia, which is more

00:22:55.505 --> 00:22:59.900
complicated than the newspapers
present in very many ways.

00:22:59.900 --> 00:23:03.930
Look at the horror show of the
Balkans in the 1990s.

00:23:03.930 --> 00:23:06.587
A lot of the issues,
religious hatreds that we

00:23:06.587 --> 00:23:09.660
thought only would be limited to
Northern Ireland.

00:23:09.660 --> 00:23:12.071
That's another theme that's
very important to the whole

00:23:12.071 --> 00:23:12.430
thing.
 

00:23:12.430 --> 00:23:15.318
Another, of course,
is economic change.

00:23:15.318 --> 00:23:17.529
Obviously, this is not a course
in economic history,

00:23:17.529 --> 00:23:20.660
but the rise of capitalism,
that's what it's called,

00:23:20.660 --> 00:23:23.450
capitalism or large-scale
industrialization.

00:23:23.450 --> 00:23:26.181
It changes in ways that we'll
suggest in the reading,

00:23:26.181 --> 00:23:29.175
and then I'll talk about a
little bit, the way people live

00:23:29.175 --> 00:23:30.700
in very fundamental ways.
 

00:23:30.700 --> 00:23:33.667
There's lot of continuities,
but there's lots of big

00:23:33.667 --> 00:23:34.250
changes.
 

00:23:34.250 --> 00:23:37.068
Everybody doesn't end up in the
assembly lines right away.

00:23:37.068 --> 00:23:41.150
